  "prompt": "Can a country run without president?",
  "response": "Yes, a country can run without a president, depending on its political structure and governance system. In some countries, different forms of government exist that do not include a presidential role. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Parliamentary Systems**: In countries with a parliamentary system, such as the United Kingdom, the head of state may be a monarch or ceremonial figure, while the head of government is the prime minister. The prime minister is usually appointed from the majority party in parliament and holds executive authority without a presidential role.\n\n2. **Collective Leadership**: Some countries operate under collective leadership, where a committee or council governs the country instead of a single president. This can be seen in certain forms of communist governance.\n\n3. **Non-Presidential Leadership**: Countries like Saudi Arabia are ruled by monarchs rather than elected presidents. The King serves as the head of state and government.\n\n4. **Transitional or Temporary Governments**: In situations of political upheaval or transition, a country might temporarily function without a president, relying on a transitional council or similar arrangement until elections can be held.\n\n5. **City-States**: Small entities like the Vatican City are governed without a president. Instead, they have other forms of leadership, such as the Pope.\n\nIn each of these cases, the absence of a president doesn\u2019t mean that the country cannot operate; it simply reflects a different structure of governance.",
